1. Core Stereotype Annotations
These annotations tell Spring which classes to manage as beans and what their roles are in
your application.

a. @Component
Purpose: Generic stereotype for any Spring-managed bean.
Usage: Place on any class you want Spring to detect and manage.
Example:

@Component
public class EmailSender {
    // Spring will create and manage this bean
}

b. @Service
Purpose: Specialization of @Component for service layer classes (business logic).
Usage: Place on service classes to clarify their role.
Example:

@Service
public class UserService {
    // Business logic here
}

c. @Repository
Purpose: Specialization of @Component for data access layer (DAO) classes.
Extra Feature: Enables automatic exception translation for database errors.
Usage: Place on classes that interact with the database.
Example:

@Repository
public class UserRepository {
    // Data access code here
}


d. @Controller
Purpose: Specialization of @Component for web controllers (MVC pattern).
Usage: Place on classes that handle HTTP requests.
Example:

@Controller
public class UserController {
    @GetMapping("/users")
    public String listUsers(Model model) {
        // Handle request and return view name
        return "users";
    }
}

2. Configuration Annotations
These annotations help you define how beans are created, configured, and managed.

a. @Configuration
Purpose: Marks a class as a source of bean definitions.
Usage: Use for Java-based configuration instead of XML.
Example:
java


@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    // Bean definitions go here
}

b. @Bean
Purpose: Marks a method as a bean producer. The method’s return value is registered as a bean.
Usage: Use inside @Configuration classes for explicit bean creation.
Example:

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    @Bean
    public EmailSender emailSender() {
        return new EmailSender();
    }
}

c. @Scope
Purpose: Defines the scope (lifetime and visibility) of a bean.
Common scopes:
"singleton" (default): One instance per Spring container.
"prototype": New instance every time requested.
"request": One per HTTP request (web apps).
"session": One per HTTP session (web apps).

Usage:

@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class UserSession {
    // New instance for each request
}

d. @Lazy
Purpose: Delays bean creation until it’s actually needed (lazy initialization).
Usage: Use on beans that are expensive to create or not always needed.
Example:

@Component
@Lazy
public class ExpensiveService {
    // Will only be created when first requested
}
